nd were moved, why they moved, and how they were kept from moving. Combining global labour history with mobility studies, it investigates moving workers through the lens of coercion. The contributions in this book are based on extensive archival research and span Europe and North America over the past 500 years. They provide fresh historical perspectives on the various regimes of coercion, mobility, and immobility as constituent parts of the political economy of labour. Moving Workers shows that all struggles relating to the mobility of workers or its restriction have the potential to reveal complex configurations of hierarchies, dependencies, and diverging conceptions of work and labour relations that continuously make and remake our world.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Bonn University Library  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aArbeit. 4aGlobalgeschichte. 4aMigration. 4aMobilität. 4aZwang. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aGlobal history.  acoercion.  alabour.  amigration.  amobility.1 aBernardi, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernardi, Claudia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGunnlaugsson, Emil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeinsen, Johan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKussy, Angelina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarcon, Gabriele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMüller, Viola Franziska, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMüller, Viola Franziska, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/e